744. corona, ‘throng‚’ used (by an obvious metaphor) in the circus, Sco.

[746—790. Aeneas pursues him, like an Umbrian dog a penned stag, Turnus calling for his own sword, Aeneas threatening death to any who aids. Aeneas’ spear had stuck in a wild olive, sacred to Faunus, which the Trojans had uprooted from the space they were clearing. Turnus prays he may not be able to draw out his weapon, and long he pulls vainly. Iuturna then gives Turnus his sword, and Venus, angry, tugs out the spear. Once more the heroes rise, and face each other.]
